'''Glenflorrie Station''', also known as '''Glen Florrie Station''', is a pastoral lease that operates as a [[cattle station]]. It is located about {{convert|147|km|mi|0}} south of [[Pannawonica, Western Australia|Pannawonica]] and {{convert|175|km|mi|0}} west of [[Paraburdoo, Western Australia|Paraburdoo]] in the [[Pilbara]] region of [[Western Australia]], and occupies an area of {{convert|1970|km2|sqmi|0}}.

It is currently owned by Murray and Aticia Grey. The Grey family have been producing [[Brahman (cattle)|Brahman]] cattle for the live export trade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenslandcountrylife.com.au/news/agriculture/cattle/beef/ambassadors-for-live-exports/84285.aspx?page=2|title=Ambassadors for live exports|date=8 April 2008|accessdate=28 April 2014|work=Queensland Country Life|publisher=[[News Limited]]}}</ref>

The property is watered by Glenflorrie Creek. It lies between the [[Ashburton River (Western Australia)|Ashburton]] and [[Henry River (Western Australia)|Henry]] Rivers,<ref name=R2/> and shares boundaries with [[Uaroo]] Station.<ref name=R1>{{cite web|url=http://archive.agric.wa.gov.au/objtwr/imported_assets/content/lwe/rpm/catman/62%20part%202.pdf|title=Station Reports|year=1980|accessdate=5 April 2014|publisher=[[Department of Agriculture and Food (Western Australia)|Department of Agriculture]]}}</ref> The [[Indigenous Australian|traditional owners]] of the area are the [[Tharrkari]] people, who currently lease and manage Ullawarra station.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wangkamaya.org.au/pilbara-languages/tharrkari-overview|title=Tharrkari â€“ The People and their Traditional Country|year=2012|accessdate=10 May 2014|publisher=Wangka Maya Pilbara Aboriginal Language Centre}}</ref>

Glenflorrie was established at some time prior to 1894.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article33109645 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Perth |date=29 September 1894 |accessdate=28 April 2014 |page=40 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In 1896 the property was running both sheep and cattle.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3092673 |title=Upper Ashburton News |newspaper=[[The West Australian]] |location=Perth |date=12 June 1896 |accessdate=28 April 2014 |page=7 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> The property was acquired by G. W. Hall at some time prior to 1900.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75549555 |title=The Northern Times. |newspaper=[[The Northern Times]] |location=Carnarvon, Western Australia |date=25 January 1908 |accessdate=28 April 2014 |page=2 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref> Hall placed the property up for auction in 1919. A this time Glenflorrie occupied an area of {{convert|630481|acre|ha|0}} and was stocked with 7,000 sheep, 300 cattle and 50 horses.<ref name=R2>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article37458480 |title=Advertising. |newspaper=[[Western Mail (Western Australia)|Western Mail]] |location=Perth |date=13 November 1919 |accessdate=28 April 2014 |page=14 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

The Higham brothers sold Glenflorrie to the Greenway brothers in 1937.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article75122678 |title=Onslow News. |newspaper=[[The Northern Times]] |location=Carnarvon, Western Australia |date=6 October 1937 |accessdate=29 April 2014 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In 1952 the original [[homestead (buildings)|homestead]] was gutted by fire. The new homestead that was being built adjoining the old one was not damaged. At this time the owner of the property was Ron Greenway.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article76089206 |title=Onslow News Items. |newspaper=[[The Northern Times]] |location=Carnarvon, Western Australia |date=15 May 1952 |accessdate=28 April 2014 |page=3 |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>

In 2009 [[Indigenous Australian|Aboriginals]] of the Thudgari people were awarded native title of some {{convert|1200|km2|sqmi|0}} in the area including Glenflorrie, [[Maroonah]] and Mangaroon Stations. The land use agreement will allow the Thudgari access to their traditional lands to hunt, gather and camp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/site-archive/rural/wa/content/2009/11/s2746637.htm|title=Thudgari people claim native title rights in the Upper Gascoyne|author=Laurissa Smith|date=18 November 2009|accessdate=4 May 2014|publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]}}</ref>

